@node "OtherPrgs" "Other programs!"

   @{MS "Other programs!"}
   @{MS "BoulderDðsh   [game/jump/boulderdaesh.lha]"}

Clone of the original Boulderdðsh for Amiga. It is the only version running faster on Amiga than the
original. It looks and behaves like the original. I was asked, where the C64 is. (-8 And all this on
a 68000 without Fastmem.

   @{MS "SimpleCat   [dev/misc/simplecat.lha]"}

This tool is for programmers and user. Using this program you can change catalogs of programs with
your favourite text editor in the easiest way. These programs must include a CS file. Search for it
in the archive of the catalogs drawer.

   @{MS "AFind   [util/misc/afind.lha]"}

With this program you can search for programs on your Aminet CDs in the easiest way. It is the same
than the original tool on the CD, but here you can use AminetCDs and AminetSets mixed. So you are
not forced to search for a program on the first 5 Aminet CDs, that is on AminetSet1 Disk b.

   @{MS "AView   [util/misc/aview.lha]"}

AView is a great multiview enhancement/replacement! It is working like Multiview, but you are able
to specify a special viewer/player for each file type.

   @{MS "Guideformat   [text/edit/guideformat.lha]"}

GuideFormat is a simple tool. It is easy to format text blocks, even if there are "links" or other
guide commands in.

   @{MS "GuideCheck   [text/edit/guidecheck.lha]"}

GuideCheck is a tool, that allows to check an entire guide file and discovers all errors!

   @{MS "SiedlerBoot   [game/patch/siedlerboot.lha]"}

This allows to start the Settlers direct via CD and save the scores on HD. There is no hard disk
install required. SiedlerBoot requires the "Amiga Plus Sonderheft 9" cover CDROM.

   @{MS "Execute64   [misc/emu/execute64.lha]"}

Execute64 allows to transfer file direct into the C64 and to start them. This allows to play games
an use the Amiga a big file server.

   @{MS "R   [util/cli/r.lha]"}

"R" creates a GUI for each DOS Programm. This allows you to use DOS commands even if you arenÇt very
good in reading templates.

   @{MS "DVBControl   [comm/misc/dvbcontrol.lha]"}

DVBControl is a software project for the Nokia MediaMaster (D-Box) and DVB2000 firmware. It allows
to update firmware, edit channel settings and much more. So if you are using DVB2000 and an Amiga
DVBcontrol is your only choise!

   @{MS "MCControl   [hard/hack/mccontrol.lha]"}

MCControl (MemoryCard Control) is a card reader for Playstation MemoryCards. It requires a little
selfmade hardware (~$5) and the free software!

   @{MS "VBRControl   [util/sys/vbrcontrol.lha]"}

VBRControl moves the processor vector base to fastram. This is increasing system speed.

   @{MS "AvailCPU   [util/sys/availcpu.lha]"}

AvailCPU is a little program that shows the CPU usage by using the PowerLED!

   @{MS "TrackDisplayClock   [util/time/trackdisplaycl.lha]"}

A hardware track display is very useful, if you need it! The most time this type of hardware is only
good for lighting up the room! This will be changed when using TrackDisplayClock! TrackDisplayClock
displays the system time on your track display! Its cool, its useful and of cource the time is
always in visual range. Delete all programs using screens, windows or icons to display the time and
of course donÇt forget to remove your noclick tool! TrackDisplayClock is doing all these jobs and
your system will be faster than before! (-8

   @{MS "MMKeyboard   [hard/hack/MMKeyboard.lha]"}

MMKeyboard is a hardware for using IBM-PC keyboards on Amiga. It allows to use multimedia keys like
Play or Pause. MMKeyboard supports any key on any keyboard! No special driver for each keyboard like
on the PC! Only one small commodity for all keyboards is required to smuggle the multimedia keys
into the system. MMKeyboard is full reset handler compatible, contains a internal hardware password,
allows to turn your Amiga on and off by using the keyboard and much more.

   @{MS "ParKeyboard   [hard/hack/ParKeyboard.lha]"}

ParKeyboard is a small hard and software project that allows you to use an Amiga keyboard connected
to the parallel port. The interface did't contain any components. Just four wires are required to
adapt the parallel port.

   @{MS "WheelMouseSupport  [util/mouse/WheelMouseSupp.lha]"}

WheelMouseSupport is a WheelBusMouse Software replacement. It allows to use the mouse wheel with most
Amiga programs without any patches.

@endnode

@node "PT_Reverse" "WheelMouseSupport: Reverse/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "Reverse/S"}

This option is reversing the directions of the mouse wheel.@{par}

If you only want to change one direction then use the @{"ReverseX" link "PT_RX"} or
@{"ReverseY" link "PT_RY"} switch.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_RX" "WheelMouseSupport: ReverseX/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "ReverseX/S"}

Changes the direction of the X mouse wheel.@{par}

If you want to change both directions then use the @{"Reverse" link "PT_Reverse"} switch.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_RY" "WheelMouseSupport: ReverseY/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "ReverseY/S"}

Changes the direction of the Y mouse wheel.@{par}

If you want to change both directions then use the @{"Reverse" link "PT_Reverse"} switch.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_WheelQualifier" "WheelMouseSupport: WheelQualifier/M/K"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "WheelQualifier/M/K"}

The specified qualifier defines the qualifier for switching the wheel direction. This allows to
use the x direction even if the mouse has only one wheel.@{par}

It's possible to specify the following strings:@{par}

LSHIFT, LSH, RSHIFT, RSH, LALT, RALT, CAPS, CAPSLOCK, CONTROL, CTRL, LCMD, LCOMMAND, RCMD, RCOMMAND,
LMB, MMB, RMB, LJB, MJB, RJB@{par}


@endnode
@node "PT_PageQualifier" "WheelMouseSupport: PageQualifier/K"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "PageQualifier/K"}

The specified qualifier declares when WheelMouseSupport should create
the @{"PageResult" link "PT_PageResult"}.@{par}

@{b}Please note that only one qualifier is possible. In addition to that the
@{"WheelQualifier" link "PT_WheelQualifier"} has a higher priority, so using the same qualifier as
PageQualifier is useless.@{ub}@{par}

It's only possible to specify the following strings:@{par}

LSHIFT, LSH, RSHIFT, RSH, LALT, RALT, CAPS, CAPSLOCK, CONTROL, CTRL, LCMD, LCOMMAND, RCMD, RCOMMAND,
LMB, MMB, RMB, LJB, MJB, RJB@{par}


@endnode
@node "PT_PageResult" "WheelMouseSupport: PageResult/K"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "PageResult/K"}

The specified qualifier will be created by the @{"PageQualifier" link "PT_PageQualifier"}.@{par}

@{b}Please note that only one qualifier is possible.@{ub}@{par}

It's only possible to specify the following strings:@{par}

LSHIFT, LSH, RSHIFT, RSH, LALT, RALT, CAPS, CAPSLOCK, CONTROL, CTRL, LCMD, LCOMMAND, RCMD, RCOMMAND,
LMB, MMB, RMB, LJB, MJB, RJB@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_LFB" "WheelMouseSupport: LFB/S Left Fire Button)"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "LFB/S (Left Fire Button)"}

This argument enables the left joystick button as fourth mouse button.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_MFB" "WheelMouseSupport: MFB/S (Middle Fire Button)"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "MFB/S (Mittlere Joysticktaste)"}

This argument enables the middle joystick button as fourth mouse button.@{par}


@endnode
@node "PT_PRI" "WheelMouseSupport: Priority/N"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "Priority/N"}

This allows to specify the task priority of WheelMouseSupport.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_TH1" "WheelMouseSupport: THRESHOLD1=TH1/N"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "THRESHOLD1=TH1/N"}

Using this option causes a speedup of the mouse wheel reaction when breaking the given threshold.
There are two thresholds: "THRESHOLD1" and @{"THRESHOLD2" link "PT_TH2"}. Their defaults are 4 and
8!@{par}

If the user is moving the wheel very fast, then WheelMouseSupport is increasing the depending on the
threshold. The numberic argument given here is equal to the required mouse wheel steps.@{par}

E.g. When using "TH1 4 TH2 8", then the wheel is working between 0 and 3 in 1:1 mode. Each wheel
step causes one cursor move. Between 4 and 7 threshold one gets activ and doubles the reaction, so
the cursor moves 8 to 14 times. When threshold two is reached the wheel steps are multiplied by
four, so the cursor is moving at least 32 times in the direction of your choise.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_TH2" "WheelMouseSupport: THRESHOLD2=TH2/N"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "THRESHOLD2=TH2/N"}

Using this option causes a speedup of the mouse wheel reaction when breaking the given threshold.
There are two thresholds: @{"THRESHOLD1" link "PT_TH1"} and "THRESHOLD2". Their defaults are 4 and
8!@{par}

If the user is moving the wheel very fast, then WheelMouseSupport is increasing the depending on the
threshold. The numberic argument given here is equal to the required mouse wheel steps.@{par}

E.g. When using "TH1 4 TH2 8", then the wheel is working between 0 and 3 in 1:1 mode. Each wheel
step causes one cursor move. Between 4 and 7 threshold one gets activ and doubles the reaction, so
the cursor moves 8 to 14 times. When threshold two is reached the wheel steps are multiplied by
four, so the cursor is moving at least 32 times in the direction of your choise.@{par}


@endnode
@node "PT_CURSOR" "WheelMouseSupport: CURSOR/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "CURSOR/S"}

@{b}This option is only available in "WheelMouseSupportNM"! When using "WheelMouseSupport" this
option is turned on by default.@{ub}@{par}

By using this switch WheelMouseSupport is sending cursor keys for wheel action.@{par}

This option allows to use the wheel within the most programs without any patch.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_CURSORONLY" "WheelMouseSupport: CURSORONLY/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "CURSORONLY/S"}

@{b}This option is only available in "WheelMouseSupportNM"! When using "WheelMouseSupport" this
option is turned on by default.@{ub}@{par}

By using this switch WheelMouseSupport only sending cursor keys for wheel action. The NewMouse
stuff is deactivated.@{par}

This option allows to use the wheel within the most programs without any patch.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PT_RETURN" "WheelMouseSupport: RETURN/S"
@toc "WheelMouseSupport"

 @{MS "RETURN/S"}

By using this switch WheelMouseSupport is sending a return key as middle mouse button. This allows
to select the selected item by pressing the wheel.@{par}

@endnode

